x--;
These operators are unique in that they can appear both in postfix form, where they
follow the operand as just shown, and prefix form, where they precede the operand. In the

x = 42;
y = ++x;
In this case, yis set to 43 as you would expect, because the increment occurs before xis assigned
toy. Thus, the line y = ++x; is the equivalent of these two statements:
x = x + 1;
y = x;
However, when written like this,
x = 42;y = x++;
the value of xis obtained before the increment operator is executed, so the value of yis 42.
