T ob;Gen() {
ob = new T(); // Illegal!!!
}
}

// Can't create an instance of T.
class Gen<T> {
T ob;Gen() {
ob = new T(); // Illegal!!!
}
}
Here, it is illegal to attempt to create an instance of T. The reason should be easy to
understand: because Tdoes not exist at run time, how would the compiler know what type
of object to create? Remember, erasure removes all type parameters during the compilationprocess.
